                            <comment id="24553" author="erikhh" created="Wed, 27 Jun 2007 00:17:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The init-method attribute is there tot specify a custom method that is to be called when all properties are set. I think it&apos;s there because the Spring philosophy is that your POJO&apos;s shouldn&apos;t have to depend framework specific interfaces or classes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is only intended to specify a custom method, not to specify a method thats called anyway because that is what is dictated by the interface the class implements. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The javadoc in the InitializingBean interface quite clearly explains this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think this is an issue, just use one option or the other.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="24554" author="asenft" created="Wed, 27 Jun 2007 00:52:16 +0000"  >
&lt;p&gt;True, it is intended to be one way or the other (either specifying an init-method or implementing InitializingBean). Though, to improve robustness, I would vote for ensuring the method is called only once. Same goes for destroy-method.&lt;br/&gt;
I think it should not be a big issue to set this straight.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Just my 2 cents,&lt;br/&gt;
Andreas&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="24620" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 2 Jul 2007 00:06:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve fixed this for 2.1 M3 and 2.0.7: The container does not invoke a specified custom init/destroy method (again) if pointing to Initializing/DisposableBean&apos;s autodetected method.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This should be available in the next 2.1 M3 and 2.0.7 snapshots.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
